column20679: Info:"Extensive area with over 800 cliffs and more than 11.500 routes. Most of them on steep and pocketed limestone. Routes cover anything from 10 m steep bouldery powerfests to 40 m long vertical routes.The best time to go is late spring (May and June) or fall (September and October). Winters are cold with snow from December until February. Summers are either warm (30C) and dry or rainy. But you can find enough shady places for the hot summer days because a lot of crags are in the woods.Several excellent camping sites can be found. Pottenstein for example. Climb when you exit your tent

column20681: opposite of the Zehnerstein. Everybody knows it as Oma Eichler. Obviously you can camp here. There are several other campsites in the neighbourhood. Cheap accomodation (appartments or local guesthouses) are easy to find.In the lower grades (up to 6b) the protection is not good. Although there are some good exceptions. And using nuts and friends can be fun.A guidebook and a road map/satnav system for the area are essential to get the most out of your time here. Kletterführer Frankenjura Band 1 and Band 2 from Sebastian Schwertner/Panico Verlag cover the whole area. Frankenjura Extreme from the same author in English is a selected guidebook with more than 2000 routes mostly in the harder grades above 7a. All books are for sale at the Campground Eichler in Untertrubach

column25706: from single to multiple pitches. There are just a few lower than 5c where most of them are around 6a/8a. Almost 90% of the climbing routes are equipped and you will only need quickdraws and 60-70 meters of single rope to repeat them. Having said that

Where to stayDuring the summer you can sleep even without a tent but during the winter having a tent setup is

column30448: Info:"A rare and beautiful rough cut gorge connecting two of the world's largest bodies of fresh water. There are 2 distinct rock types here offering roofs
column30463: fossils and jet black squirrels.  All this within a few klicks of the mighty Niagara Falls.  The Niagara Glen experiences all 4 seasons to their fullest relative potentials
column30464: so plan accordingly.  (i.e. summer is hot and humid
column30467: winter is cold).  Here you'll find a rather large collection of limestone blocks which have mainly fallen from the headwall above and subsequently come to rest on the Canadian portion of the Niagara Gorge.  There is as well a healthy smattering of sandstone deposited below the limestone layer appearing closer to the river which manifest as both \"cave\" and water-worn egg like blocks
column30468: some of which protrude from the gorgeside.  An interesting aside: It is thought by some geologists that significant portions of the Niagara River Gorge were cut by the Falls in a mere matter of weeks as the falls crushed their way from lake Ontario towards lake Erie.  Much of the limestone/dolostone here is over 400 million years old and is full of fossil remnants.This area
column30470: offers a large range of rock quality.  All I can say is that the best lines are quite good.  The grades currently range from v0 to v12 and the usual potentials abound.  It has been said that the moderate grades are better represented here than the harder lines
column30471: and while there may be a modicum of truth to this statement
column30473: this is likely an outdated sentiment.  Indeed
column30474: there are classics at all levels if you know where to look.  This being said
column30475: the Glen encompasses a somewhat large area covering several kilometers from end to end and while there are a number of dense concentrations
column30476: much of the climbing is spread out.  The classics of each grade may be hidden at first but the intrepid will surely reward themselves with quality bouldering and its associated stoke.An important word about Access etc: It should be said that the Glen boulders live in a very special climatic zone known as a Carolinian forest (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carolinian_forest) which houses rare plant and animal species protected by the Provincial Nature Preserve in which it resides.  The Niagara Glen is apparently home to some of the only remaining Carolinian Forest in all of Canada. Local climbers have worked exceedingly hard with land managers to secure access to the bouldering in exchange for some basic behavior modifications.  These modifications largely revolve around common sense as it applies to delicate organisms in addition to other user groups (see \"Access Information/Issues\" to the left) and should be explored further via the Ontario Access Coalition website (www.ontarioaccesscoalition.com) prior to visiting the area."

column44656: Info:"north facing crags in the south of Spain. High in elevation (1000 m) so good in late spring and fall. Hot in summer and very cold in winter. 2 very different cliffbands. The upper one is vertical to slightly overhanging with grades from 4 to 8a. The lower much bigger wall is steeper with lots of tufas. Grades from 5b to 8c. You probably need to climb 6c to get the most from it. From the Loja service station on the A92 follow a rough dirt track parallel to the highway and after 2 km turn right uphill for another 3 km to the parking below the cliffs."
